        <section classes="classref-introduction-group" ids="description" names="description">
            <title>Description</title>
            <paragraph><strong>SubViewport</strong> Isolates a rectangular region of a scene to be displayed independently. This can be used, for example, to display UI in 3D space.</paragraph>
            <paragraph><strong>Note:</strong> <strong>SubViewport</strong> is a <reference internal="True" refuri="class_viewport#class-viewport"><inline classes="std std-ref">Viewport</inline></reference> that isn't a <reference internal="True" refuri="class_window#class-window"><inline classes="std std-ref">Window</inline></reference>, i.e. it doesn't draw anything by itself. To display anything, <strong>SubViewport</strong> must have a non-zero size and be either put inside a <reference internal="True" refuri="class_subviewportcontainer#class-subviewportcontainer"><inline classes="std std-ref">SubViewportContainer</inline></reference> or assigned to a <reference internal="True" refuri="class_viewporttexture#class-viewporttexture"><inline classes="std std-ref">ViewportTexture</inline></reference>.</paragraph>
            <paragraph><strong>Note:</strong> <reference internal="True" refuri="class_inputevent#class-inputevent"><inline classes="std std-ref">InputEvent</inline></reference>s are not passed to a standalone <strong>SubViewport</strong> by default. To ensure <reference internal="True" refuri="class_inputevent#class-inputevent"><inline classes="std std-ref">InputEvent</inline></reference> propagation, a <strong>SubViewport</strong> can be placed inside of a <reference internal="True" refuri="class_subviewportcontainer#class-subviewportcontainer"><inline classes="std std-ref">SubViewportContainer</inline></reference>.</paragraph>
